    "summary": "Heraclitus of Ephesus (c. 535–475 BC) was one of the most original and difficult of the Presocratic philosophers, known in antiquity as 'the obscure' for his deliberately cryptic aphoristic style — he believed that most people are incapable of understanding deep truth and should be challenged rather than condescended to. His central philosophical insights — that all things are in constant flux ('you cannot step into the same river twice'), that opposites are unified ('the road up and the road down are the same road'), and that the Logos (rational principle) governs all change — were foundational for Western philosophy.\n\nHeraclitus proposed fire as the fundamental element, not as a static substance but as a symbol of perpetual transformation: everything flows (panta rhei), all things are constantly changing into their opposites, and what appears stable is merely the balance of opposing forces. His concept of the Logos as a universal rational principle underlying the apparent chaos of change influenced the Stoics enormously (see [[event:1195|Stoicism Founded]]), who took up his Logos concept and developed it into their own doctrine of divine reason permeating the universe. The Gospel of John's opening ('In the beginning was the Logos') also draws on this tradition. Heraclitus's aristocratic contempt for popular opinion and his insistence on paradox as a tool of philosophical insight made him a favorite reference for later thinkers including Hegel.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heraclitus",
